                <div class="col-md-8">
                    <p class="pad20">I am  an educator, ethno botanist and researcher. My ethno botanical research interests are aimed at identifying, promoting and conserving useful plant species. I am principally interested in documenting plant use, and researching the effects of such use on the exploited plant populations. To understand the second aim, I am  studying plant population structures and plant biology. I am a Professor of Ethno botany and now lecturing in the College of Agricultural and Environmental Sciences. I have  16 years of teaching experience at University level. I quickly rose through the ranks from Assistant Lecturer in 1995 to full Professor in 2010. As a hardworking academic, I have so far supervised 2 PhD and10 Masters Graduates. I have  published 25 referred papers, five chapters in five books and one book. I have  attended over 40 conferences, seminars, workshops and symposia and presented several papers. I have  also organized several national and international conferences, workshops, seminars and symposia from which over 40 reviewed papers were published in special issues of the African Journal of Ecology. I have  participated in 20 research projects and consultancies supported by various national and international agencies including UNESCO, IFS, VicRes, WHO,PFARD-COMPAS Uganda Project, the Garden Club of America, International FOREAIM project, Sida-SAREC, I@mak.com, NUFU, NORAD and PROTA. I am also a  professional member of a number of local and international organizations including International Society of Ethno biology, Association for the Taxonomy Study of the Flora of Tropical Africa [AETFAT] and Nature Uganda among others. I have also been fortunate enought to get invited to a  number of fellowships and recieve a number of awards including the Dennis Stanfield Memorial Fund, International Foundation for Sciences [IFS], and Anne S. Catham Fellowship in Medicinal Botany among others..</p>
